## Little's Law — The Core Concept

This formula is actually a fundamental principle from queuing theory called **Little's Law**:

> *"The average number of items in a system equals the arrival rate multiplied by the average time each item spends in the system."*

```
L = λ × W

L = concurrent items in the system (in-flight requests)
λ = arrival rate (how many arrive per second)
W = average time each item spends in the system (latency in seconds)
```

It's beautifully simple — let's build intuition from scratch.

---

## Real World Analogy First

Imagine a **restaurant kitchen**:

- The kitchen can handle **27 orders simultaneously** (your thread pool capacity)
- Each order takes **3 minutes** to cook (downstream latency)
- How many new orders per minute can arrive before the kitchen is overwhelmed?

```
27 orders in kitchen = arrival_rate × 3 minutes
arrival_rate = 27 / 3 = 9 orders per minute
```

If orders arrive **faster than 9/minute**, they pile up → kitchen collapses.

**Your Spring app is that kitchen. Async threads are the chefs.**

